<span id="freeTextContainer14041329540481433721">There are places where it&apos;s amusing because it was written 35 years ago. They tried to be contemporary and included some computer and Silicon Valley slang that never caught on and just sounds hilariously outdated now. Nevertheless, I appreciated the maps and the reminders of other things that I&apos;ve read elsewhere before. And it did make me think about the various people I&apos;ve met from other parts of the world, some of whom I get to work with occasionally. It&apos;s also been long enough since I&apos;ve read</span>
  <span id="freeText14041329540481433721" style="display:none">There are places where it's amusing because it was written 35 years ago. They tried to be contemporary and included some computer and Silicon Valley slang that never caught on and just sounds hilariously outdated now. Nevertheless, I appreciated the maps and the reminders of other things that I've read elsewhere before. And it did make me think about the various people I've met from other parts of the world, some of whom I get to work with occasionally. It's also been long enough since I've read a book on English that I've been exposed to a broader range of authors and performers, so it reminds me to be even more open to all of that. If I had read this back when it came out (and seen the PBS show) I would've have probably loved it. But since because this is yet another book on a subject I've read before, I appreciate it, but didn't love it.</span>
