<div id="review_3284429870" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3284429870" />
    <a title="Fraser Sherman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17613779-fraser-sherman"><img alt="Fraser Sherman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1362087433p2/17613779.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3284429870?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Fraser Sherman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Fraser Sherman" href="/user/show/17613779-fraser-sherman">Fraser Sherman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780142002315" href="/book/show/207742.The_Story_of_English">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17613779-fraser-sherman?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3284429870" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15753394294488337346">A companion volume to a 1980s PBS series on how English evolved and spread around the world. While it lacks the pleasure of hearing different accents and tones, it&apos;s a little easier than going through the videos searching for a particular fact.<br/>This traces the development of English from the Indo-European ancestral tongue through Gaelic and Anglo-Saxon, the Norman conquest and the steady acquisition of words from other countries and races (slaves and colonial possessions contributed plenty). Alon</span>
  <span id="freeText15753394294488337346" style="display:none">A companion volume to a 1980s PBS series on how English evolved and spread around the world. While it lacks the pleasure of hearing different accents and tones, it's a little easier than going through the videos searching for a particular fact.<br />This traces the development of English from the Indo-European ancestral tongue through Gaelic and Anglo-Saxon, the Norman conquest and the steady acquisition of words from other countries and races (slaves and colonial possessions contributed plenty). Along the way there are constant class pressures trying to create one standard English and the vibrancy of the language going Nope.<br />The book ends with a look at how Spanglish, Singlish (Singapore English) and other hybrids are splintering off and whether they'll eventually become a separate, incomprehensible language.<br />Detailed, thorough and fascinating.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15753394294488337346" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

