  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2972228785" />
    <a title="Michael Goodine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/99502039-michael-goodine"><img alt="Michael Goodine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609074779p2/99502039.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2972228785?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael Goodine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael Goodine" href="/user/show/99502039-michael-goodine">Michael Goodine</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780142002315" href="/book/show/207742.The_Story_of_English">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2972228785" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9846413135272719354">An interesting look at the history of the English language, with a special focus on all of the regional variations found around the world. The first chapter, about how the language has achieved supremacy in the current era, is a little bit tedious but the rest of the book is quite interesting. Along with the results of his research and interviews, the author includes a number of interesting anecdotes and digressions along the way to keep things fun for readers.<br/><br/>Note that contrary to what is expre</span>
  <span id="freeText9846413135272719354" style="display:none">An interesting look at the history of the English language, with a special focus on all of the regional variations found around the world. The first chapter, about how the language has achieved supremacy in the current era, is a little bit tedious but the rest of the book is quite interesting. Along with the results of his research and interviews, the author includes a number of interesting anecdotes and digressions along the way to keep things fun for readers.<br /><br />Note that contrary to what is expressed in some other reviews, the book <i>has</i> been updated - in 1993 and 2002. That said, most of the revisions seem to have been done in '93. I can't see any obvious references to the 21st century here.</span>
  <a data-text-id="9846413135272719354" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


